<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>The Magic Numbers Group Home Page</H1>

Welcome the the home page of the Magic Numbers group.  We are
attempting to evolve a semantic file typing system for the Internet
and World Wide Web by building on existing Unix "magic number"
conventions. <P>

Our near-term goals are:
<UL>
<LI> To design an Internet registry for magic numbers (i.e. data stream 
   patterns describable in the language of file(1)) comprising a de-facto 
   semantic file type system. <P>

<LI> To develop an Internet RFC promulgating guidelines for choosing magic
   numbers and defining standards for "magic-number-aware" programs based
   on the registry. <P>

<LI> To develop from file(1) a reference library of routines usable in 
   magic-number-aware programs. <P>
</UL>

Once the magic numbers RFC and the Magic Numbers Registry have been developed,
the group may take on other challenges, including extension of the file(1)
specification language to be able to get hints from filename patterns. <P>

The charter members of the group were Eric S. Raymond, Daniel Quinlan,
Christos Zoulas, and Greg Roelofs.  Others have since joined.  You
can view the <A HREF="http://www.catb.org/~esr/magic-numbers/magic-numbers-list">mailing list roster</A> here. <P>

If you believe you can contribute, you can join by <A
HREF="mailto:esr@thyrsus.com">sending mail to the moderator</A>.
We're particularly interested in participation by people with
experience in developing Web browsers or navigating the RFC standards
track.<P>

You can browse an <A HREF="http://www.catb.org/~esr/magic-numbers/mail-archive">HTML archive</A> of the mailing list. <P>

You can read the <A HREF="http://www.catb.org/~esr/magic-numbers/rfc-draft">RFC draft</A> and a list of
<A HREF="http://www.catb.org/~esr/magic-numbers/open-issues.html">open issues</A>.  The draft is nowhere near ready
for official submission yet, but motivates and records our discussion. <P>

This page was, rather unaccountably, chosen as <A
HREF="http://www.owlnet.rice.edu/~indigo/gsotd">Geek Site Of The
Day</A> on January 28 1996.

